\maketitle
Profinite group is an inverse limit of finite groups.

I will define the cohomology of profinite group and Brauer group.

\section{discrete G-modules}
Let G be a profinite group and A a left G-module. And U is an open subgroup of G.

$A^{U}$ is the set of all fixed elements in A under U.

When $A = \cup{A^{U}}$, we call A discrete G-modules.

Following three conditions are equivalent.

(i) A is a discrete G-module
(ii)the stabilizer in G of every module elements is an open subroup of G
(iii) the pairing $G\times A \rightarrow A$ is continuous (A is viewed as a discrete space.)

The proof is easy and just use elementary topology.

\section{defitition of restriction and inflation map}
Since cohomology group is a contravariant functor about group, injection $G \rightarrow G'$ induces 
a homomorphism $H^{a}(G,A) \rightarrow H^{q}(G',A)$ for any G-module A.

it is called the restriction homomorphism.

If H is a normal subgroup, $A^{H}$ is a G/H-module. 

Because cohomology group is a contravariant functor about group and covariant fuctor about G-mocule,

We can induce maps $H^{q}(G/H,A^{H}) \rightarrow H^{q}(G,A^{H})$ and $H^{q}(G,A^{H}) \rightarrow H^{q}(G,A)$

Composing these two maps give us a inflation map $H^{q}(G/H,A^{H}) \rightarrow H^{q}(H,A)$

